  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">When PlaybookDispatcher returns a match with OutputType="dialog" and RequiresConfirmation=true, the SSE stream contains a `dialog_open` event with `codePage` and `fields` properties</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">When PlaybookDispatcher returns a match with OutputType="text" and RequiresConfirmation=false, the response streams normally via the standard chat flow</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">When PlaybookDispatcher returns OutputType="download", a file download link is returned to the client (not a dialog)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">When PlaybookDispatcher returns no match (Matched=false), the handler falls through to the standard SprkChatAgent response flow unchanged</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">PlaybookOutputHandler is NOT in the DI container (factory instantiation verified)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`dialog_open` event data includes the pre-populated field values extracted by PlaybookDispatcher (ExtractedParameters mapped to Code Page field names)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`dotnet build` passes with no errors</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    The Code Page name for the `dialog` output type comes from the JPS definition — it is stored as
    a field in the playbook's output node (e.g., `output.codePage: "sprk_emailcomposer"`). The
    `PlaybookDispatcher` reads this from JPS and includes it in `DispatchResult.OutputType` context.
    Verify how the code page name flows from JPS to `DispatchResult` — it may need to be a separate
    field on the result model (e.g., `DispatchResult.CodePageName`) rather than embedded in OutputType.

    The `navigate` SSE event type (for `navigation` output) is also new. Add it alongside `dialog_open`
    in the `ChatStreamEvent` discriminators in step 2. Document both new event types in
    `notes/018-new-sse-event-types.md` for the frontend Phase 3 tasks to consume.

    For autonomous actions (RequiresConfirmation=false), the handler should emit a brief confirmation
    text response to the user: "I've completed {action}." This keeps the user informed even when no
    dialog opens. Use the agent stream to emit this as a standard `token` event followed by `done`.
  </notes>

